 ''big apple '' is a nickname for new york city . 
 ''the big apple '' was popularized as a name for new york city by john j .  fitz gerald in a number of horse-racing articles for the `` new york morning telegraph '' in the 1920s . 
by the late 1920s ,  new york writers other than fitz gerald were starting to use `` big apple '' and were using it in contexts other than horse-racing . 
fitz gerald referred to the `` big apple '' frequently thereafter . 
the earliest known usage of 'big apple' appears in the book `` the wayfarer in new york ''  -lrb-  1909 -rrb- ,  in which author edward s .  martin writes: kansas is apt to see in new york a greedy city .  .  . 
fitz gerald reportedly first heard `` the big apple '' used to describe new york's racetracks by two african american stable hands at the famed new orleans fair grounds . 
